metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #371
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord.

metadata.name: Einstein-Rosen Memories #44
metadata.description:
At first this was 'just' an attempt at visualizing my childhood imagination of wormholes.
As I worked on the code and the more the fusion of music and visuals took me over, the more this piece led me to deeper thoughts.
How vague can something be in order to really exist?

Well, this, of course raised many new questions.
Questions about space-time, about metaphysical assumptions, about the transmission of thoughts and feelings and so on.

The longer you ask yourself about these things, the more the boundary between fiction and reality becomes blurred, because there really is none.

///
Click for audio.
png screenshot: 's' in live view (I highly recommend doing this!).

No rarity features this time, your taste decides.
The music was written and recorded on December 15th, 2020 on a Tascam 4-track tape recorder. 

PLEASE NOTE:
The thumbnails do not reflect the actual artwork.
(See them as another layer of vague memories)

///
Created with Hydra

metadata.name: Blockchain Automaton #256
metadata.description:
This experimental project involves an on-chain cellular automaton. The features and cellular automaton rules are derived from the minter's address. Being the first (unto my knowledge) project on fxhash that generates the artwork completely on chain, it seemed fitting to draw inspiration from one of the first projects on fxhash, "RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton".

What is this?

An experimental generative token that integrates on-chain generation, and on-chain storage of the artwork. This is accomplished using a custom smart contract. The artwork is generated using the generate_on_chain entrypoint in KT1GRFujk5m6feK7gJcqCU7ijJkFgx5JigEt, and the generated image is subsequently stored on-chain as a byte-string of pixels (row-major order) in the tokens bigmap in KT1GRFujk5m6feK7gJcqCU7ijJkFgx5JigEt.

How does this work?

Smart contracts have a default entrypoint which is automatically called when XTZ is sent to the contract. By using a smart contract as the primary address, the default entrypoint will be called every time a token is minted. Of course, to prevent accounts from bypassing the fxhash contracts and sending XTZ directly to the smart contract, generating and storing the artwork on-chain, the smart contract checks that an fxhash contract is the account sending XTZ. In this smart contract, the default entrypoint immediately calls the generate_on_chain entrypoint for the sole purpose of making the generation process more apparent on indexers like tzkt.

In order to make this project compatible with fxhash, the artwork produced by the code submitted to fxhash must be identical to that which is produced by the generative algorithm within the smart contract. At the time of development, the minter's address is the only piece of information which is readily accessible via the fxhash snippet API and in the smart contract. As a result, each account can only generate a single unique artwork (this is enforced by the contract). In the future, this issue could be solved if the fxhash snippet API provided access to the iteration number, as the smart contract could also keep track of this information quite easily.

Consequently, collectors who wish to collect more than one iteration must create additional accounts to mint. The tokens can then be subsequently transferred as per usual.

Why is the variations preview disabled?

Because the minter's address is the source of randomness for the generated artwork, not the hash provided by fxhash, changing the hash in the variations preview will have no effect. To see different variations of the artwork you need to modify the fxminter URL parameter in live preview mode.

Why does the mint button not work on the fxhash frontend?

Currently, the fxhash frontend has a default storage limit for mint operations that is less than what is required to store the generated image on chain. As a result, the mint button will fail on the fxhash frontend. To get around this, you can mint this token on a mini-website I created (https://blockchain-automaton.netlify.app/), or on Better Call Dev, or by injecting the transaction directly onto the blockchain.

But Why?

Because experimentation is fun.

metadata.name: Indistinct Places #87
metadata.description:
There's a certain state you fall into when you're half asleep that feels very warm and nostalgic. Most of the time, you imagine places or situations that are a mixture of the familiar and the unfamiliar, a strange brew of your past and the future you desire.
"Indistinct Places" is a tribute to this fuzzy state.

/////

Takes a long time to render.
In case you get bored: click on the canvas to start the algorithmic audio.

key "1" - "6": increases the render resolution by 2x with each step
-> These will automatically export a png after the simulation is done.
(Alternatively, you can contact me on Twitter and i can render a high res file in the size you need).

key "s": saves a png with the current resolution

Tone.js is used for the audio.

As in a dream, this representation flows, changes direction and evolves.

Some have two faces, one light and one dark where sleep flows. Others have a central theme from where our dream is born or dies, in hope or in despair. Others, just flow.

metadata.name: Ceremony #356
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I’m so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. 🥂

Definitely check out “Forever” mode by tapping “F” or mouse click/tap — it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will “never forget” and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that’s a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses “…Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.” Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : “Forever” mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start “Forever” mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in “Forever” mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending “&density=2” (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: The Fringe #8
metadata.description:
We are innately aware of our bodies' position through perception of space. If we are visibly surrounded by walls with flooring under, a ceiling above, and a window facing the sky, we know we are inside of an enclosed space, with a view of outside. But how does a room stopped being an enclosed space? Can a space with 3 walls be considered a room? If we are surrounded by walls but our ceiling is gone, then are we inside or outside? This is an exploration on the edges of our ability to perceive space. The fringes that instill some fear in our mind. And that fear is failing to make sense of our position in a space that slowly loses its tangibility.

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
It may take a few seconds to render, depending on the device.

created using WEBGL on p5.js
dirbots - Jan23

metadata.name: Meltdown #37
metadata.description:
Abstract painting. Anything can melt, given the right temperature.

Project written in vanilla Javascript.

The drawing is executed at window resolution.

Press '2' to double the resolution. You can press again '2' to double once more;
Press '1' to get back at the window size.
Press 'l' to cycle the layers. This only works while rendering.
Press 's' to save a png at the current resolution. You can also right click and 'save-as' to obtain the same result.


It uses two external packages, both licensed under MIT license:
* https://www.npmjs.com/package/file-saver
* https://www.npmjs.com/package/simplex-noise
